<DOC><DOCNO> AP880726-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1206EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0503 07-26 0674</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,0689</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Belt Much Of The Nation</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 6th graf, `Elsewhere in ...,' toUPDATE with storm knocking out electricity in Michigan. Picks up in7th graf, `In Missouri ...</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the nation today, bringingrain to drought-parched land, after severe storms belted theMidwest and South with tornadoes, lightning, hail and fierce windsthat killed two people.   A cold front hammered violent storms through the central UnitedStates on Monday, producing severe weather in Michigan, Missouriand Illinois.   In Arkansas, a late evening thunderstorm whipped up high windsthat caused widespread damage around Pine Bluff. One person waskilled when a tree was blown onto an occupied car.   In Michigan, lightning struck and killed a Jackson County womanas thunderstorms packing winds up to 60 mph raced across thestate's southeastern Lower Peninsula, knocking out power tothousands.   Two tornadoes ripped through southeastern Michigan Mondayafternoon and a third touched down a few hours later, uprootingtrees and damaging crops near the eastern town of Lapeer.   Elsewhere in Michigan, thunderstorms unleashed winds that downedlarge trees near Alma, Saginaw County and Lapeer County and hail upto an inch in diameter.   The storm knocked out power to 20,288 Consumers Power Co.customers in the southern Lower Peninsula; power was restored thismorning to all but 5,480 customers, company spokesman Kelly Farr.About 1,200 Detroit Edison Co. customers scattered across southeastMichigan also lost power, but only about 150 were without powerthis morning, the utility said.   In Missouri, thunderstorms generated high winds that downedtrees near Buffalo, Nevada, Cape Girardeau and Blodgett.   Thunderstorms developing along the same cold front producedsevere weather at a few places in Illinois, Kansas and Oklahoma.   In Illinois, farmers hoping for a little rain instead saw cropsbattered by damaging hail as storms moved across the state,stripping leaves off plants and causing spotty power outages fromChicago to southern Illinois.   More than 2 inches of rain fell at Cooksville in McLean County,while more than 1.5 inches fell in Chicago and Springfield.   Foul weather across central and south Florida damaged homes,uprooted trees, downed power lines and left potholes up to 2 feetlong in a runway at Miami International Airport apparently causedby lightning strikes.   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstormsover portions of the southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley,the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and inland areas of the northern andmiddle Atlantic Coast, lso over the south Atlantic coastal statesand eastern portions of the Gulf Coast states; and widely scatteredthunderstorms near Lake Superior and across the mountain areas ofthe Western states.   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s along the PacificCoast and the shores of the upper Great Lakes and in northernMaine, between 95 and 105 degrees through the southern Plains,western portions of the northern Plains and lower elevations westof the Rockies; between 105 and 115 in the desert Southwest; andbetween the 80s and low 90s throughout the rest of the UnitedStates.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 94 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 76 partly cloudy; Boston 70 foggy; Buffalo 69cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 77 foggy; Cincinnati 66 foggy; Cleveland65 showery; Detroit 63 partly cloudy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; NewYork 74 fair; Philadelphia 73 hazy; Pittsburgh 67 cloudy; Portland,Maine 63 foggy; Washington 76 hazy.   _Central: Bismarck 62 partly cloudy; Chicago 67 fair;Dallas-Fort Worth 80 fair; Denver 70 cloudy; Des Moines 64 fair;Indianapolis 66 foggy; Kansas City 66 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 67fair; Nashville 74 cloudy; New Orleans 74 fair; St. Louis 70 foggy.   _West: Albuquerque 80 partly cloudy; Anchorage 60 fair; LasVegas 93 fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 96 cloudy; Salt LakeCity 74 fair; San Diego 70 hazy; San Francisco 59 fair; Seattle 73fair.   _Canada: Montreal 70 fair; Toronto 66 foggy.</TEXT></DOC>